    {
        "content": "<p>still sad my own keyboard doesn't have F13-F24</p>",
        "id": 535367181,
        "sender_full_name": "Aaron Liu",
        "timestamp": 1755713653
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Right, that's why I bought a split keyboard with ortholinear parts. This way you can tilt both parts accordingly.</p>\n<p>The parts also spin slightly on the axis that follow the forearm so you don't end up twisting your arm with the thumbs downwards and the small fingers upwards to type on a flat surface. The difference is HUGE.</p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"https://cdn.mos.cms.futurecdn.net/LzqkZQVJGRVobeDtQ9rNwF.jpg\"><img src=\"https://uploads.zulipusercontent.net/4de748f633e9be1f7fda1a57d79eb079bfdbcc86/68747470733a2f2f63646e2e6d6f732e636d732e66757475726563646e2e6e65742f4c7a716b5a51564a4752566f626544745139724e77462e6a7067\"></a></div>",
        "id": 535367188,
        "sender_full_name": "Arthur Paulino",
        "timestamp": 1755713657
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"511228\">Huỳnh Trần Khanh</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113488-general/topic/Stenography.20and.20Lean.204/near/535366759\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>There are cursed keycaps out there that turn staggered keyboards into ortholinear keyboards...</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Unlike the standard keyboard, which is awkward for the left hand, ortholinear (square grid) keyboards are awkward for <em>both</em> hands. Unless you split it in two halves and put them far apart.</p>",
        "id": 535369455,
        "sender_full_name": "suhr",
        "timestamp": 1755714626
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Iirc, it’s probably worth mentioning in this thread the difference between ortholinear keyboards and columnar keyboards (where the columns are staggered to match finger length differences). The keyboard in <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"451983\">@Arthur Paulino</span>’s message (the ZSA moonlander, perhaps?) looks to me to have slightly staggered columns instead of being a true ortholinear!</p>",
        "id": 535370534,
        "sender_full_name": "Thomas Murrills",
        "timestamp": 1755715097
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(Aside: I’ve heard good things about the Moonlander! If I had the desk setup to accommodate it, I’d seriously consider investing in one…)</p>",
        "id": 535370990,
        "sender_full_name": "Thomas Murrills",
        "timestamp": 1755715307
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hm, my keys are ortholinear (they truly follow the shape of the fingers), but they don't form a grid! They keys for the middle columns go a bit further away. This is another detail that improves the adjustment for my hands.</p>",
        "id": 535371085,
        "sender_full_name": "Arthur Paulino",
        "timestamp": 1755715349
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm not getting any money from this. I'm just being honest about my experience <span aria-label=\"sweat smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f605\" role=\"img\" title=\"sweat smile\">:sweat_smile:</span></p>\n<p>I wish the best for anyone who spends several hours everyday on a computer, like I do.</p>",
        "id": 535371391,
        "sender_full_name": "Arthur Paulino",
        "timestamp": 1755715496
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, I was under the impression “ortholinear” specifically meant having the keys arranged on a square grid (i.e. “along perpendicular lines”), while “columnar” referred to the arrangement you see there, where each finger’s keys are in a column, and the columns are staggered!</p>",
        "id": 535376258,
        "sender_full_name": "Thomas Murrills",
        "timestamp": 1755717525
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The definitions seem to vary across different sources, but you got the idea</p>",
        "id": 535378329,
        "sender_full_name": "Arthur Paulino",
        "timestamp": 1755718318
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"816344\">Aaron Liu</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/113488-general/topic/Stenography.20and.20Lean.204/near/535367122\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I want all the keys</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This is a mistake. The maximum number of keys that you can have in a comfortable keyboard is 42 (six keys for index and pinky fingers, three keys for the other fingers). Above that number there are keys that are more than one key away from your rest position. I don’t have any keyboard with more than 36 keys (only three keys per pinky finger), but some people like 42 keys. Then of course I have many layers which give me access to many more symbols and macros than what you get on a non-configured 105 keys keyboard. And Leo de Moura also uses such keyboards, so the discussion is settled anyway.</p>",
        "id": 535418523,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Massot",
        "timestamp": 1755744077
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Fun coincidence: I just gave a talk about Lean to high school students in Hangzhou and all questions after the talk were about my keyboard (a chocofi keyboard in this case).</p>",
        "id": 535418581,
        "sender_full_name": "Patrick Massot",
        "timestamp": 1755744135
    },
